NODE_12_length_49651_cov_254.638621	MetaGeneAnnotator	CDS	35143	35610	.	+	0	ID=MGA_862;product=hypothetical protein;inference=COORDINATES:ab initio prediction:MetaGeneAnnotator;translation=MDTLPITTPRQAGIYVRQAREAQGITRAALAKKAGVSERLLASLELGDATGIRLDKLLAIFDALELALAAQGDISETKNEHPVDAPHADQPCSTSRRHHAQRLHHRNRRSTTIPALADTPLTSELYDRAFADFAMSNLGVSIAANASSQTMPEGK;locus_tag=LOCUS_08550;note=TIGR:TIGR03070%3B couple_hipB: transcriptional regulator%2C y4mF family [Name:TIGR03070%2C Eval:1.1e-13%2C score:48.9%2C bias:1.5],Domain:cl15354:CBS_pair N/A. CBS domains are small intracellular modules that pair together to form a stable globular domain. This family represents a single CBS domain. Pairs of these domains have been termed a Bateman domain. CBS domains have been shown to bind ligands with an adenosyl group such as AMP%2C ATP and S-AdoMet. CBS domains are found attached to a wide range of other protein domains suggesting that CBS domains may play a regulatory role making proteins sensitive to adenosyl carrying ligands. The region containing the CBS domains in Cystathionine-beta synthase is involved in regulation by S-AdoMet. CBS domain pairs from AMPK bind AMP or ATP. The CBS domains from IMPDH and the chloride channel CLC2 bind ATP. [Superfamily%2C Aligned:1-65%2C Eval:5.9e-07%2C score:44.0%2C C-term missing],MGA_862
